      "description": "*Alaska*'s dense arrangements — multiple time signature changes, simultaneous genre shifts in the guitars and vocals, and constant dynamic variation — demanded a snare that could deliver authority at peak intensity while remaining sensitive enough for the ghost note work that appears across the album's quieter sections. Richardson's DW Collector's maple snare at 14\" x 6.5\" balanced both demands.\n\nThe maple shell construction delivers a warm crack rather than the sharp attack of steel or aluminum alternatives. At medium-high tension, it cuts through the dense dual-guitar arrangements on *Alaska*'s most extreme passages — on \"The Primer\" and \"Selkies: The Endless Obsession,\" the snare drives through a wall of distorted guitar without becoming harsh. The 6.5\" depth provides the body needed for snare authority in progressive metal's dense frequency environment.\n\nFor *Alaska*'s more restrained sections — the folk interludes, the jazz passages, the quiet dynamics that make the heavy sections land harder — Richardson's ghost note work on the DW Collector's maple delivers the subtle, controlled touch that these moments demand. Evans G2 Coated batter heads provided the two-ply control and slightly dampened sustain appropriate for the full range of *Alaska*'s technical and dynamic demands.",
