      "description": "By the time of *The Parallax II*, Richardson's DW Collector's Series kit had been refined through seven years of BTBAM touring and recording — including three landmark albums (*Alaska*, *Colors*, *The Great Misdirect*) that had made him one of progressive metal's most respected drummers. The kit configuration remained consistent with his established setup, but Richardson's relationship with his gear had deepened into the kind of intimate familiarity that allows a drummer to play with complete attention on the music rather than the instrument.\n\nThe DW Collector's maple shells continued to provide the warm fundamental that anchors *The Parallax II*'s massive dynamic range. The album's concept — a science fiction narrative spanning multiple realities — requires musical vocabulary that can move from intimate, quiet passages to full orchestral-scale intensity within minutes. The Collector's Series maple construction delivers across this entire range: it sustains beautifully in the ambient and jazz sections and responds with immediate authority during the album's most extreme metal passages.\n\nFor *The Parallax II* specifically, the kit's three rack tom configuration (10\", 12\", 13\") proved essential for the fill architecture that connects the album's narrative sections. Richardson's fills throughout *Telos* and *Lay Your Ghosts to Rest* are compositional statements — they mark structural transitions, prepare the listener for harmonic shifts, and serve the concept's narrative arc. The wide pitch range of the three-tom setup gives these fills melodic dimension that a two-tom configuration could not provide.\n\nJamie King's production at Basement Studios captured the kit with the same intimate understanding he had developed across multiple BTBAM records. The drum sound on *The Parallax II* is warm and present without dominating the dense orchestration — Richardson's kit sits in the mix as one voice among many complex elements rather than as a backdrop.",
      "notes": [
        "DW Collector's Series — seven years of BTBAM touring refinement from Alaska through Colors",
        "Same core configuration as Alaska/Colors era — familiarity enabling maximum musical attention",
        "Three rack toms (10\", 12\", 13\") essential for Parallax II's compositional fill architecture",
        "Jamie King at Basement Studios captured the kit with seven records of intimate production knowledge"
      ],
