      "size": "14\" x 6.5\"",
      "shell": "Maple",
      "description": "*The Parallax II* demands more snare versatility than any previous BTBAM record. The album moves from blast-beat-adjacent passages in the opening of \"Telos\" to the restrained, jazz-influenced phrasing of \"Bloom\" — and the snare must serve both extremes convincingly. Richardson's DW Collector's 14\"x6.5\" maple continues to balance authority and sensitivity across this wider demand.\n\nAt peak intensity — the double-bass passages and rapid alternation sections in \"Telos\" and \"Lay Your Ghosts to Rest\" — the DW Collector's maple delivers the cutting authority that drives through the dense guitar and keyboard orchestration. During *The Parallax II*'s more restrained passages, the same snare handles Richardson's ghost note work and subtle dynamic control without the stiffness that many high-tension performance snares exhibit.\n\nEvans G2 Coated batter heads give Richardson the two-ply warmth and controlled sustain that his technique requires across both extreme contexts. The coating adds the texture that ghost notes benefit from — slightly increased stick resistance that improves the articulation of very quiet strokes at the edge of the head's playing surface.\n\nBy *The Parallax II*, Richardson's relationship with this snare configuration was fully established. The DW Collector's maple 14\"x6.5\" appears across BTBAM's most important records and represents the snare voice the band's audience identifies with Blake Richardson's playing.",
