    "faq": [
      {
        "question": "What drum kit did Blake Richardson use on The Parallax II: Future Sequence?",
        "answer": "Blake Richardson recorded *The Parallax II: Future Sequence* (2012) using a refined DW Collector's Series kit — the same core configuration (double 22\" bass drums, 10\"/12\"/13\" rack toms, 16\" floor tom) he had used across *Alaska* and *Colors*, now seven years into its evolution through intensive BTBAM touring. He paired the kit with Meinl Byzance Dark and Extra Dry cymbals (an expansion from the single-series Extra Dry setup of earlier albums) and the DW 9002 double bass pedal. Producer Jamie King recorded the album at Basement Studios in Winston-Salem, NC. Full profile: [Blake Richardson at MetalForge](/drummer/blake-richardson)."
      },
      {
        "question": "What makes Telos the most studied track on The Parallax II?",
        "answer": "\"Telos\" is widely regarded as Richardson's most compositionally developed recorded performance on *The Parallax II*. The track features multiple metric modulations across its arrangement, varying kick density from dense double-bass passages to restrained single-foot patterns, and fill architecture that marks narrative transitions in the album's science fiction concept. Richardson's ability to execute these complex rhythmic elements while serving the track's emotional arc — rather than displaying technique for its own sake — makes \"Telos\" the definitive study in his approach. The track demonstrates every aspect of his technique: [metric modulation](/technique/odd-time-signatures), ghost note work, compositional double-bass deployment, and anticipatory fill architecture that prepares listeners for transitions before they arrive."
      },
      {
        "question": "Why did The Parallax II earn Grammy consideration?",
        "answer": "*The Parallax II: Future Sequence* earned Grammy consideration as a progressive metal record of genuine compositional ambition — 74 minutes of concept-driven music that demonstrated BTBAM's place in serious progressive rock tradition while maintaining extreme metal credibility. *Prog Magazine*'s Album of the Decade designation reflected the critical consensus: the album is a complete statement of what progressive metal can accomplish when musicians commit fully to the format. Richardson's drumming is central to that achievement — his performance across nine extended tracks demonstrates the kind of musical intelligence that is rare in any genre, not just metal. The comparison cluster includes [Matt Halpern (Periphery)](/drummer/matt-halpern) and the progressive metal tech-drummer lineage that BTBAM helped define."
      },
      {
        "question": "How do the Dark and Extra Dry Meinl Byzance series differ on The Parallax II?",
        "answer": "On *The Parallax II*, Blake Richardson used both the Byzance Dark and Extra Dry sub-series to cover the album's expanded dynamic range. The Byzance Dark series features warmer, more complex tones with more overtone richness and slightly longer decay — suited to the album's jazz-influenced and restrained passages, where cymbal complexity adds harmonic texture without cluttering the musical space. The Byzance Extra Dry series delivers drier, more focused sounds with faster decay and less wash — suited to the album's complex rhythmic passages where clarity of articulation is essential. The 14\" Dark Hi-Hats, 18\" Dark Crash, and 10\" Dark Splash serve the warmer musical contexts; the 17\" Extra Dry Thin Crash and 20\" Extra Dry Ride serve the more precise rhythmic demands. Both series share the hand-hammered Byzance construction that provides the complex overtone character distinguishing them from machine-made alternatives."
      }
    ],
    "conclusion": {
      "title": "Progressive Metal at Its Most Ambitious",
      "content": "*The Parallax II: Future Sequence* is the document of Blake Richardson at his creative peak. Seven years into BTBAM's most productive period — from *Alaska* through *Colors*, *The Great Misdirect*, and the *Parallax* EP — the 2012 full-length is the culmination of everything those records built. The result earned *Prog Magazine*'s Album of the Decade designation and placed BTBAM in conversation with the greatest progressive metal records of the 21st century.\n\nRichardson's DW Collector's Series kit, expanded Meinl Byzance Dark and Extra Dry cymbal vocabulary, and DW 9002 double pedal gave him the tools to serve 74 minutes of concept-driven music that demands everything from blast-beat extremity to jazz-influenced restraint. The gear is not the story; it is the platform that allowed the musical story to be told.\n\nFor drummers studying the Parallax II:\n- **Full profile**: [Blake Richardson at MetalForge](/drummer/blake-richardson)\n- **Entry point**: [Alaska drum setup (2005)](/articles/alaska-drum-setup) — where the BTBAM arc begins\n- **Successor**: [Coma Ecliptic drum setup (2015)](/articles/coma-ecliptic-drum-setup) — the progressive rock opera that followed\n- **Odd-time techniques**: [Odd time signatures in metal drumming](/technique/odd-time-signatures)\n\n*The Parallax II* is the record that made it impossible to argue with Blake Richardson's place among progressive metal's greatest drummers."
    },
