      "description": "By *Coma Ecliptic*, Richardson's DW Collector's Series kit had been refined through a full decade of BTBAM touring and six studio albums — *Alaska*, *Colors*, *The Great Misdirect*, *Parallax EP*, *The Parallax II*, and now *Coma Ecliptic*. The kit was not an instrument being explored; it was an extension of Richardson's musical vocabulary, completely understood and deployed with total confidence.\n\nFor *Coma Ecliptic*'s rock opera structure, the DW Collector's maple shells needed to serve a more narratively focused musical context than the previous BTBAM records. The album's chapters — each representing a different alternate reality in the protagonist's coma — required the kit to adapt to varied musical environments within a unified production aesthetic. The Collector's Series maple handled this demand convincingly: warm and resonant in the album's more melodic sections, powerful and authoritative in the heaviest passages, subtle and controlled during the quieter narrative moments.\n\nThe three-rack-tom configuration (10\", 12\", 13\") continued to enable the melodic fill architecture that has been Richardson's signature since *Alaska*. In *Coma Ecliptic*'s more melodic context, these fills function more as narrative punctuation — marking chapter transitions in the rock opera's story — than as technical demonstrations. The wide pitch range gives Richardson the tools to make these narrative fills melodically meaningful.\n\nProducer Jamie King had now recorded seven BTBAM records with Richardson, making Basement Studios the most familiar recording environment in the band's history. The *Coma Ecliptic* drum sound reflects this familiarity — warm, present, and balanced, with Richardson's kit captured as the natural center of the album's orchestration.",
