      "shell": "Maple",
      "description": "*Coma Ecliptic*'s rock opera structure placed different demands on Richardson's snare than the previous BTBAM records. The album's more deliberately melodic context meant fewer blast-beat passages and more sustained dynamic storytelling — the snare needed to be a narrative voice as much as a rhythmic anchor.\n\nThe DW Collector's 14\"x6.5\" maple continued to serve these demands through its warm, versatile character. Tuned at the medium-to-medium-high setting Richardson favored across the BTBAM catalog, the snare delivered authority without harshness — appropriate for a record that wanted to reach wider audiences without sacrificing tonal quality. On *Coma Ecliptic*'s heavier chapters, the maple snare still drove through dense guitar arrangements with the authority progressive metal requires. On the more restrained melodic chapters, the same snare handled softer backbeats and nuanced dynamic control with equal ease.\n\nThe consistency of this snare choice across the BTBAM catalog is itself a significant production decision. Listeners who follow the band across albums hear the same snare voice evolving in musical context rather than a different instrument. The DW Collector's maple 14\"x6.5\" is audibly the same instrument across *Alaska*, *Colors*, *The Parallax II*, and *Coma Ecliptic* — it anchors the band's sonic identity as much as any other single piece of gear.",
